Here's the complete migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

Your code has **3 patterns** that all break in .NET 8:

| Location | Pattern | Why it breaks |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | ASP.NET request termination | Internally calls `Thread.Abort` → `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | Redirect with `endResponse=true` | The `true` param triggers `Thread.Abort` to halt execution |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control-flow exception swallowing | `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown in .NET 6+; dead code |

## Migrated Code (ASP.NET Core / .NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // Was: btnExport_Click with Response.Write + Response.End()
    // Now: Return a FileContentResult — the framework handles headers and
    // response completion. No need to manually Clear/End the response.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    // Was: btnRedirect_Click with Response.Redirect(url, true) + ThreadAbortException catch
    // Now: Return RedirectResult — execution continues after the return,
    // so no abort or exception is involved.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // ThreadAbortException catch block removed entirely —
        // Redirect() in ASP.NET Core just returns a result object,
        // it never throws.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

**1. `Response.End()` → just `return`**
ASP.NET Core has no `Response.End()`. Returning an `IActionResult` signals the framework to finish the response. Use `File(...)` for downloads — it sets `Content-Type` and `Content-Disposition` for you.

**2. `Response.Redirect(url, true)` → `return Redirect(url)`**
The `true` parameter existed solely to call `Thread.Abort` and halt execution. In ASP.NET Core, `Redirect()` returns a result object — execution naturally stops at `return`. No abort needed.

**3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → removed**
This block only existed to swallow the exception that `Response.Redirect(url, true)` threw. Since `Redirect()` never throws, the catch is dead code. Remove it entirely.

**4. `User.Identity.IsAuthenticated` → null-safe check**
In ASP.NET Core, `User.Identity` can be `null` for unauthenticated requests. Use `?.IsAuthenticated ?? true` to avoid `NullReferenceException`.

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Writing to Response then returning an IActionResult** | Don't mix `Response.Body.WriteAsync()` with returning `IActionResult`. Pick one. If you return `File(...)`, the framework owns the response. |
| **Expecting code after `Redirect()` won't execute** | In WebForms, `Response.Redirect(url, true)` aborted the thread so nothing below ran. In Core, `Redirect()` returns an object — code after it **will** execute unless you `return`. Always `return Redirect(...)`. |
| **Catching `ThreadAbortException` "just in case"** | It will never be thrown. Leaving dead catch blocks masks real bugs if someone later adds code that throws a different exception. |
| **Using `[Authorize]` instead of manual auth checks** | ASP.NET Core has `[Authorize]` attribute — prefer it over manual `IsAuthenticated` checks. The manual check above is kept for direct parity. |

## Recommended Improvement (use `[Authorize]`)

```csharp
[Authorize] // Framework handles redirect to login automatically
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
{
    try
    {
        ProcessRequest();
        return Redirect("/success");
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        LogError(ex);
        return Redirect("/error");
    }
}
```

Configure the login redirect once in `Program.cs`:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddAuthentication().AddCookie(options =>
{
    options.LoginPath = "/login";
});
```

This eliminates the manual auth check entirely and centralizes the login redirect path.
